json.query:
MATCH (n)
WHERE ((n.name IN $entity_names
      OR ANY(ename IN $entity_names WHERE toLower(n.name) CONTAINS toLower(ename))
      OR ANY(ename IN $entity_names WHERE toLower(ename) CONTAINS toLower(n.name)))
      OR toLower(n.name) IN [x IN $entity_names | toLower(x)]
      OR ANY(ename IN $entity_names WHERE size(ename) > 3 AND toLower(n.name) CONTAINS toLower(ename)))
  AND (n.tenant_id = $tenant_id OR n.tenant_id IS NULL)
WITH n,
     CASE
       WHEN n:Organization THEN 1.3
       WHEN n:Person THEN 1.2
       WHEN n:City THEN 1.1
       WHEN n:Museum THEN 1.2
       WHEN n:Technology THEN 1.0
       WHEN n:Disease THEN 1.0
       ELSE 0.9
     END as entity_priority
ORDER BY entity_priority DESC
LIMIT 10

OPTIONAL MATCH path = (n)-[r*1..3]-(m)
WHERE (m.tenant_id = $tenant_id OR m.tenant_id IS NULL)
WITH path, n as startNode, entity_priority,
     reduce(score = entity_priority, rel IN relationships(path) |
       score + CASE type(rel)
         WHEN 'A_CREE' THEN 1.5
         WHEN 'CAUSE_PAR' THEN 1.4
         WHEN 'CONNECTE' THEN 1.3
         WHEN 'PROTEGE_CONTRE' THEN 1.3
         WHEN 'ETUDIE' THEN 1.2
         WHEN 'UTILISE' THEN 1.2
         WHEN 'CIBLE' THEN 1.2
         WHEN 'EXPOSE_A' THEN 1.1
         WHEN 'VISE_A_LIMITER' THEN 1.1
         WHEN 'SOUS_ENSEMBLE_DE' THEN 1.0
         WHEN 'ETEND' THEN 1.0
         ELSE 0.8
       END
     ) as path_score,
     length(path) as path_length

WHERE path_score > (path_length * 0.3)

RETURN
  startNode.name as start_entity,
  [node IN nodes(path) | {name: node.name, type: labels(node)[0]}] as path_nodes,
  [rel IN relationships(path) | type(rel)] as path_relations,
  path_score,
  path_length
ORDER BY path_score DESC
LIMIT $max_results
json.hyde_document:
PING (Packet Internet Groper) is a computer network administration utility used to test the reachability of a host on an Internet Protocol (IP) network. It measures the round-trip time for messages sent from the originating host to a destination computer and back. PING operates by sending Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) echo request packets to the target host and waiting for an ICMP echo reply. The program reports errors, packet loss, and a statistical summary of the results, typically including the minimum, maximum, the mean round-trip times, and standard deviation of the mean.

The name PING comes from active sonar terminology that sends a pulse of sound and listens for the echo to detect objects underwater. In computing, PING is used to verify whether a particular IP address exists and can accept requests. The echo request is an ICMP message whose data is expected to be received back in an echo reply. PING measures the round-trip time and records any packet loss.

When a PING command is issued, the utility sends several ICMP echo request packets to the target host. Each packet contains a timestamp, which is used to calculate the round-trip time. The target host, upon receiving the echo request, responds with an ICMP echo reply packet. The PING utility then calculates the time taken for the packet to make the round trip.

PING is a valuable tool for network administrators to troubleshoot network connectivity issues. It can help identify network latency, packet loss, and whether a host is reachable. The utility is available on most operating systems, including Windows, macOS, and Linux, and is often used in conjunction with other network diagnostic tools.

In summary, PING is a fundamental network diagnostic tool that uses ICMP echo requests and replies to measure the reachability and round-trip time of hosts on an IP network. Its simplicity and effectiveness make it an essential utility for network troubleshooting and performance monitoring.

json.hyde_document:
PING (Packet Internet Groper) is a computer network administration utility used to test the reachability of a host on an Internet Protocol (IP) network. It measures the round-trip time for messages sent from the originating host to a destination computer and back. PING operates by sending Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP) echo request packets to the target host and waiting for an ICMP echo reply. The program reports errors, packet loss, and a statistical summary of the results, typically including the minimum, maximum, the mean round-trip times, and standard deviation of the mean.

The name PING comes from active sonar terminology that sends a pulse of sound and listens for the echo to detect objects underwater. In computing, PING is used to verify whether a particular IP address exists and can accept requests. The echo request is an ICMP message whose data is expected to be received back in an echo reply. PING measures the round-trip time and records any packet loss.

When a PING command is issued, the utility sends several ICMP echo request packets to the target host. Each packet contains a timestamp, which is used to calculate the round-trip time. The target host, upon receiving the echo request, responds with an ICMP echo reply packet. The PING utility then calculates the time taken for the packet to make the round trip.

PING is a valuable tool for network administrators to troubleshoot network connectivity issues. It can help identify network latency, packet loss, and whether a host is reachable. The utility is available on most operating systems, including Windows, macOS, and Linux, and is often used in conjunction with other network diagnostic tools.

In summary, PING is a fundamental network diagnostic tool that uses ICMP echo requests and replies to measure the reachability and round-trip time of hosts on an IP network. Its simplicity and effectiveness make it an essential utility for network troubleshooting and performance monitoring.
